    "summary": "The Battle of Dien Bien Phu, fought from March to May 1954 in a remote valley in northwestern Vietnam, resulted in a decisive defeat of French colonial forces by the Viet Minh communist independence movement and effectively ended French rule in Indochina. French commanders had established a fortified base at Dien Bien Phu intending to lure the Viet Minh into a conventional battle where French firepower would destroy them. Instead, Viet Minh General Vo Nguyen Giap used tens of thousands of soldiers and civilian laborers to haul heavy artillery over jungle mountains and establish overlook positions that neutralized the French airstrip and rendered the base indefensible.\n\nAfter 57 days of siege, the remaining 11,721 French and allied troops surrendered on May 7, 1954 — the day before the opening of international negotiations in Geneva. The psychological and political impact of the defeat far exceeded its immediate military significance. France had lost 2,293 killed and had over 10,000 taken prisoner, many of whom died in captivity. The defeat demonstrated that European colonial forces could be beaten by Asian guerrilla armies using determination, mass mobilization, and unconventional tactics.\n\nThe battle led directly to the [[event:3463|Geneva Accords of 1954]], which temporarily divided Vietnam at the 17th parallel and set the stage for the [[event:2674|Vietnam War]] that would engage the United States in the following decades. Dien Bien Phu became a global symbol of anti-colonial resistance and shaped military thinking about counterinsurgency for a generation.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Dien_Bien_Phu",
